{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491560","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491560"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:52:51+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:52:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"982"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"982","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/982"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.44,0.09,0.06,0.04,0.37]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"982"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110544"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"982","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/982"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"982"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92801"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1871"},{"type":"tags","id":"3470"},{"type":"tags","id":"3662"},{"type":"tags","id":"3696"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4984"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8609"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8643"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41763"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42188"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43827"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110544","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/110544"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA previously well 58-year-old man presents with a two day history of profuse diarrhoea and crampy lower abdominal pain. There is no blood in the stool. The previous day he had returned from a one-week holiday in Bali. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination he appears listless, with dry mucus membranes, a blood pressure of 100/70 mmHg, pulse 100/min and temperature 37.0\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC. He has no peritonism on examination of the abdomen.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe is admitted to hospital and in the next 24 hours he has \u0026gt;6 episodes of watery stool and requires 6L of intravenous fluid.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely causative organism of his symptoms?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Enterotoxigenic E. coli","Campylobacter","Salmonella","Shigella","Vibrio cholerae"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has traveller\u0027s diarrhoea and a severe form; sufficiently serious to have led to profound dehydration and hypovolaemia. There are many different causative organisms and of the listed agents, the two most likely to explain this patient\u0027s illness would be \u003Cstrong\u003EEnterotoxigenic Escherichia coli\u003C/strong\u003E (ETEC) and Vibrio cholerae. These two organisms produce a secretory diarrhoea. By far the most common of these two organisms is ETEC and until proven otherwise, this should be considered the most likely cause in a patient presenting with this form of diarrhoea.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInfection with ETEC is the commonest cause of travellers\u2019 diarrhoea and is an important cause of diarrhoeal disease in lower-income countries, particularly amongst children. However, in some areas of the world, such as Bangladesh, cholera remains the commonest form of secretory diarrhoea. ETEC is transmitted by food or water contaminated with animal or human faeces. The incubation period is usually one to three days and the excretion of ETEC may be prolonged.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECampylobacter\u003C/strong\u003E is one of the commonest causes of bacterial gastroenteritis and the symptoms often include fever, stomach cramps and diarrhoea, which is often bloody. This is different from the clinical picture shown by this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESalmonella\u003C/strong\u003E is a less likely cause of this patient\u0027s diarrhoea. The typical symptoms in these patients include fever, nausea and vomiting and the diarrhoea contains blood and/or mucus. It would not be watery, as in this case. \u003Cstrong\u003EShigell\u003C/strong\u003Ea gastroenteritis has a very similar picture to salmonella infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECholera\u003C/strong\u003E is not endemic in Australia and it is rarely seen. There are only about six documented cases a year in this country. However, with the frequency of overseas travel, particularly to areas of the world where the disease is endemic, the possibility of cholera must always be considered in individuals who present with high volume watery diarrhoea. Travellers at higher risk of Vibrio cholerae infection include those who drink or eat contaminated water or food and in particular undercooked or raw shellfish and fish. Cholera is also associated with poor sanitation. The incubation period is two hours to five days and the organism will remain in the faeces for one to two weeks after infection. Transmission from person to person is very uncommon. The risk of cholera can increase following natural or man-made disasters due to the disruption of water and sanitation systems or the displacement of populations to overcrowded camps.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPost script: this scenario is based on a real case. Whilst the patient was initially thought - on the basis of probability - to have an ETEC infection, the initial faecal microscopy was unhelpful and it was only the subsequent culture that showed large number of highly mobile bacilli, together with large volumes of watery stool that a diagnosis of cholera was made. After 36L of intravenous fluid and electrolyte replacement, the patient was discharged home following six days of hospitalisation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENonetheless, the question is asking the \u0027most likely causative agent\u0027 which is ETEC for being the most likely cause of traveller\u0027s diarrhoea.\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Enterotoxigenic Escherichia coli is the commonest cause of travellers\u0027 diarrhoea."],"references":["Devitt P, Shaw D, Lim I.  Cholera in Adelaide.  Med J Aust.  1992, 157: 68-69.","Kanungo S, Azman AS, Ramamurthy T, et al. Cholera. Lancet. Lancet 2022; 399: 1429\u201340."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92801"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"982"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92801","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92801"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-01T09:13:26+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-01T09:13:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"982"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110544"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id"